subsection.subsubsection:
Limit Laws

	 Limit Laws

		Suppose that c is a constant, and that the limits \ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) and \ds \lim_{x\to a} exist.  Then,



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x) \pm g(x)] = \ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) \pm \lim_{x\to a} g(x)



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} [cf(x)] = c\cdot \lim_{x\to a} f(x)



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x)\cdot g(x)] = \lim_{x\to a} f(x)\cdot \lim_{x\to a} g(x)



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} \dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \dfrac{\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x)}{\ds \lim_{x\to a} g(x)}, provided that \ds \lim_{x\to a} g(x)\neq 0



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x)]^n = \left[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\right]^n



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} c = c



				\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x)]^{1/n} = \left[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\right]^{1/n}, where n  is a positive integer (we assume the limit is positive if n is even)





Each of these can be restated in words:



		Sum/Difference Rule: The limit of a sum/difference of functions is the sum/difference of the limit of the functions.



		Constant Multiplier Rule: The limit of a constant times a function is the constant times the limit of the function.



		Product Rule: The limit of a product of functions is the product of the limits.



		Quotient Rule: The limit of a quotient of functions is the quotient of the limits (provided the denominator is nonzero).



		Power Rule: The limit of a function raised to a power is the power of the limit of the function.



		Constant Rule: The limit of a constant is a constant.



		Root Rule: The limit of the nth-root of a function is the nth-root of the limit of a function.




