	Direct Substitution Property
	Direct Substitution Property


		If f is a polynomial, rational, or algebraic function with a in the domain of f, then \ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a)




	Calculate the following limits.  Justify each answer with one (or more) of the limit laws.



			\ds \lim_{x\to -1} 3x^3+5x^2-7




			\ds \lim_{x\to 2} \dfrac{x^3+2x^2-1}{5-3x}




			\ds \lim_{x\to 1} \dfrac{x-1}{x^2+1}








			\ds \lim_{x\to -1} 3x^3+5x^2-7 = -9.  Since this is a polynomial, you can use the direct substitution property.




			\ds \lim_{x\to 2} \dfrac{x^3+2x^2-1}{5-3x}=-15.  Since this is a rational function with 2 in the domain, we can use direct substitution.




			\ds \lim_{x\to 1} \dfrac{x-1}{x^2+1}=0.  Since this is a rational function with 1 in the domain, we can use direct substitution.







	Let k(x)=\dfrac{x+1}{x^2-1}.



			The Direct Substitution Property cannot be applied to the function at x = -1.  Why not?



			Modify the function so that you can use the Direct Substitution Property.







			-1 is not in the domain



			Factor the denominator as (x+1)(x-1) and cancel to get \dfrac{1}{x-1}.

