Assume that \ds \lim_{x\to 3} f(x) = -1, \ds \lim_{x\to 3} g(x) = 2, and \ds \lim_{x\to 3} h(x) = 0.  Find the following limits, if they exist.  If they don't, explain why.  Justify each answer with the appropriate limit law(s).



		\ds \lim_{x\to 3} [f(x) + 5g(x)]



		\ds \lim_{x\to 3} [f(x)]^5



		\ds \lim_{x\to 3} \sqrt{g(x)}



		\ds \lim_{x\to 3} \dfrac{3f(x)}{g(x)}



		\ds \lim_{x\to 3} \dfrac{g(x)}{h(x)}



		\ds \lim_{x\to 3} \dfrac{f(x)h(x)}{g(x)}

Compute the following limits:



		\ds \lim_{t\to -5} g(t), where g(t) = \begin{cases}t^2 -1 \amp t\neq -5\\ \pi+1 \amp t = -5 \end{cases}




		\ds \lim_{h\to 0} \dfrac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}, where f(x) = x^2+2x-1




		\ds \lim_{h\to 0} \dfrac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}, where f(x) = \sqrt{x}

